From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Apr 26 00:00:00 2026
Subject: [PATCH] gdb/python: guard _PyOS_ReadlineTState for Python 3.13+

Python 3.13 stopped nulling the interpreter thread state during
PyOS_Readline and dropped _PyOS_ReadlineTState from the public API
(see CPython gh-105908).  GDB 14.2's py-gdb-readline.c still references
the variable unconditionally, which fails to compile on hosts shipping
Python 3.13 / 3.14 (CachyOS, Arch).

Guard the save/restore pair on PY_VERSION_HEX < 3.13.0.  On older
Pythons the dance is still required; on 3.13+ the thread state is
already valid in the catch handler so the explicit restore would be a
no-op anyway.

This matches the upstream GDB fix on master and Fedora's gdb-14
backport.

--- a/gdb/python/py-gdb-readline.c
+++ b/gdb/python/py-gdb-readline.c
@@ -56,12 +56,16 @@ gdbpy_readline_wrapper (FILE *sys_stdin, FILE *sys_stdout,
       if (except.reason == RETURN_QUIT)
 	return NULL;

+#if PY_VERSION_HEX < 0x030d0000
       /* The thread state is nulled during gdbpy_readline_wrapper,
 	 with the original value saved in the following undocumented
 	 variable (see Python's Parser/myreadline.c and
 	 Modules/readline.c).  */
       PyEval_RestoreThread (_PyOS_ReadlineTState);
+#endif
       gdbpy_convert_exception (except);
+#if PY_VERSION_HEX < 0x030d0000
       PyEval_SaveThread ();
+#endif
       return NULL;
     }

